The paper deals with distance oracles in planar graphs, which are a fundamental topic in theoretical computer science and have applications in various fields such as network routing and geographic information systems. The main focus is on tradeoffs between space and query-time, which are central to the study of data structures and algorithms. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also involves geometric and combinatorial aspects of planar graphs, which suggest the sub-categories cs.CG (Computational Geometry) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). Moreover, the paper uses techniques from information theory and coding theory to achieve the tradeoffs, which relate to cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.SI (Systems and Control).
